Animate a choropleth

Feasibility of a slider filter

John Little

2019-03-13

Backdrop: I spent several hours trying to use the crosstalk or plotly packages to generate a suitable choropleth with a slider filter. The purpose of the slider filter should enable filtering by year so the enduser can see change over time. In practice this proved to be unfeasible or unworkable. The annimation transitions were sloppy or goofy; the slider wouldnt work as expected. In short the idea proved much easier than the exectution.

However, the resulting investigation show me several aspects about the practical execution of showing change over time. I am shorthand documenting some of those issuse here.

Load Library Packages

First, lets load the necessary pacakges.

library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(sf)
library(gganimate)

Get Data

Now lets get some ACS Census data and then scramble the data. By scramble what I mean is randomize the data so that its easier to see the changes over time. Since the data re scrabled, theres really no need to know what the actual census variable means, but Im pretty sure I started with population for North Carolina covering 2013 - 2016.

nc_2016 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2016")
nc_2015 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          year = 2015,
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2015")
nc_2014 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          year = 2014,
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2014")
nc_2013 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "county",
          variables = "B01003_001",
          state = "NC",
          year = 2013,
          geometry = TRUE,
          cache_table = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(year = "2013")

Wrangle Data

Combine the small tables into a big table. Make a copy of the same with scrambled data via sample(). Additionally, make a scrambled table wihtout sf geometry for use in the barplot.

big_table <- rbind(nc_2016, nc_2015, nc_2014, nc_2013) 
nc_2016_r <- nc_2016
nc_2015_r <- nc_2015
nc_2014_r <- nc_2014
nc_2013_r <- nc_2013
nc_2016_r$estimate <- sample(nc_2016_r$estimate)
nc_2015_r$estimate <- sample(nc_2015_r$estimate)
nc_2014_r$estimate <- sample(nc_2014_r$estimate)
nc_2013_r$estimate <- sample(nc_2013_r$estimate)
bg_r <- rbind(nc_2016_r, nc_2015_r, nc_2014_r, nc_2013_r)
bg_r_nogeom <- bg_r
sf::st_geometry(bg_r_nogeom) <- NULL  # remove geometry layer from the SF Tibble

Facet Map

Facet Maps are amazingly effective at showing change. Perhaps this is actually better than animating. Its certainly far less work useing the facet_wrap() function.

ggplot(bg_r) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate, color = estimate)) +
  coord_sf(crs = 4326, datum = NA) +
  facet_wrap(~year)

NA

Bar Plots

Sometimes geography is not the best way to showcase data, even when the data have a geographical element. The next plot visualizes the change over time for three countie in a side-by-side bar graph. The change over time is much more obvious when the yearly amount for relevant counties are positioned next to each other.

Side-by-side bargraphs are a ggplot option useing position = "dodge".

A time-change question that is easier to answer with a bargraph than a choropleth is as follows: Which county has the highest annual amount for the year 2014?. Compare this question by looking at the choropleth facet map above and the bargraph below.

bg_r_nogeom %>% 
  mutate(county = str_extract(NAME, "\\w+")) %>% 
  filter(county == "Mecklenburg" | 
           county == "Durham" | 
           county == "Guilford") %>% 
  select(county, estimate, year) %>% 
  gather("foo", "year", -county, -estimate) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = county, y = estimate, fill = year), 
           position = "dodge") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d()

Annimate

p <- ggplot(bg_r) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = estimate, color = estimate)) +
  coord_sf(datum = NA) +
  labs(title = '{next_expression}') +
  transition_filter(transition_length = 0.4, 
                    filter_length = 0.4,
                    year == "2013",
                    year == "2014",
                    year == "2015",
                    year == "2016") +
  enter_fade() +
  exit_fade() +
  shadow_mark(past = TRUE, future = TRUE)

animate(p)
